value.0: A gruff looking man with an ill air about him.
The Living Guard are renowned for their skill, and despite the state of their former home, they remain dangerously organized.

This helmet has been exquisitely forged from adamantine, its sinisterly beautiful design typical of drow craftsmanship. A small letter "V" has been interwoven into the pattern upon the visor.

Adamantine is an extraordinarily hard alloy that is almost impenetrable to normal weapons. Deposits of adamant are usually found near areas of Faerzress in the Underdark, and to the Deep Denizens it is usually black in colour, though it possesses a green sheen when viewed by natural light or a purple-white sheen when viewed by magical light.

Before you stands a mage who eyes you with suspicion, as if expecting anyone to be an assassin or some such other.
These robes are infused with a darkly, vile magic, and they're splatted with much blood. You absently wonder about their creation.

Many moons ago, the City of Tarkuul existed in a much sinister glory, whence some crusading paladins raized it and naught but the gate bars remained.

You now hold one of these bars, unrusted by time, since Tarkuul's sinister magic has steeped into it's shaft.

This portly man stands beside various boxes of trading goods with a notebook in hand, seemingly always taking inventory.  Most notably this man has an eye patch, which for some reason matches that of the dog beside him.

A rather odd-looking man with a half-mop of hair on  his head!
A scythe similar to the one used by the fabled Grim Reaper - a supposed myth...

Clad in fine leather and chain armor this gruff sounding yet sophisticated looking man is clearly one of authority within the Moorhound Company. With a gait of an experienced swordsman, he seems as one who is most familiar and comfortable on the high seas.

This armor seems to be the ceremonial regalia of a Maskarran priest.  Done in a motley pattern, this clothing emphasizes freedom of movement and speed over all things.  It also has an unusual side effect: while wearing this clothing, thoughts of larceny and ways to attempt it come unbidden to your mind.
This wand will allow a seasoned tracker to identify any one creature within a zone.
A strange looking creature peers at you - Not quite human, but what exactly it is, remains a mystery to most.
A black robe.  Fine for walking about town, and being seen at the Nomad.  Not very practical for battle however.
Pallid skin and a left arm devoid of flesh mark this individual clearly as a Palemaster.

Kenku are small, halfling sized humanoids with the body features (feet, head, body covred in feathers) of a crow or a raven. They have working, prehensile talon ended hands, but no wings, and are exceptionally good at working together. Many Kenku become thieves, using their teamwork skills to pull off impressive heists.
